text: I so hope this isn't the last we see of McKellan and Stewart. That'd just break my heart. This looks like it'll be the best X movie since X2 going away. So glad to have Singer back. You can already see in they sleek production design and clean lines that we might finally see his clean style again after Ratner and Vaughn's gaudy excess. And Jackman as Wolverine goes up there with Conroy as Batman as one of those definitive character interpretations. Looks like Singer might finally bring back the A-game and make a movie which just might compete with the Marvel studios stuff. Maybe we'll finally see the fulfillment of that promise that's been botched since X2 for over a decade. I'm in.

text: It's getting really hard to figure out the timelines just from the trailers; Prof X is seen both walking and in a wheelchair, and there are inconsistencies with the timeline of the original trilogy. Maybe this whole story starts with the villain going back in time, bringing with him the engineering knowledge necessary to build the first sentinels; this could change up the entire future, essential re-writing everything that happened in the original trilogy. That would make sense, and it would explain the multiple timelines: 1st. Original timeline with "First Class" and the previous movie trilogy. 2nd. New timeline created by the villain going back in time and creating sentinels. 3rd. New timeline created by wolverine having his consciousness sent back to stop the sentinels 4th???. Maybe wolverine has to get sent back again by the younger Professor X, or anything else could happen resulting in another timeline.

text: An opinion of one diehard X-Men fan regarding the cinematic universe, well I have been reading the comics since the 80's so I know a thing or two about these guys;) Even when I was a kid I told my Mom that Magneto and Xavier reminded me of Malcolm X and Martin Luther King.  ¬†Ok, here goes, I will admit that they have screwed some things up, but there were some good things as well, the first film was just ok (in hindsight), X-2 was Awesome the opening with Night Crawler was Freakin' sick!!On the money, so comic like, X-3 was terrible but it had a few high points here and there, and it was ambitious I'll give it that, and First Class was very good.  Now on to Days of future past, it unfortunately looks very different from the comic book, because everything in the X-Men CU has to revolve around Jackman...oh, I mean waay too tall Wolverine, I can't hate though he has done an amazing job. Though it is supposed to be Kitty's story, and they added so many characters that were not there, and bitched out Cyclops and seemingly removed him all together WTF! But I digress, the first two trailers for DOFP looked interesting, (beside that weird editing sh*t in the 1st trailer, were it's quite then Wolverine yells and the out of place music blast on level 11 out of nowhere, yeah wow, ok breathe dude;), anyways, this 3rd and final trailer looks Freakin' DOPE!! I'm in.  ...And please Singer, don't...let...us...down.¬†

text: Honestly, ¬†Not sure I like this T2 sort of plot. ¬†I mean hasn't the Machines target everyone thing a bit overdone? ¬†Just saying.  This is a small gripe, but still one I can't shake for some reason. ¬†I'd really like it if the Sentinels were just targeting mutants and stayed that way. ¬†Then the distopian future was, 'well there are no mutants because the humans committed genocide again.' ¬†And then the film could touch on the X-men's larger themes of tolerance and unity vs. intolerance, racism, fear, etc. with a side focus on the cyclical nature of attack and retaliation and escalating violence. ¬†And instead of the Nazi's doing it, its us in a society that's modeled after our own.  It could be a pretty heady mix, but instead it takes what seems to be the cheap and easy route to say that the humans created AI and the AI took over.  Don't get me wrong, still think it will be an awesome movie, just a little more worried now after this trailer.

author: SetiteWonder

text: To all the comic book nerds/fan boys who think they are super cool for knowing everything that happens in the comics...shut the F*** up.¬† Seriously, not everyone has had the chance (or the money) to read every single damn comic made for X-Men but we may know enough of the character's backgrounds to have some appreciation for the original material.¬† What you have to understand is that the original comics were, more than likely, not written for purposes of being turned into a movie.¬† If Bryan Singer, and other comic book movie directors, directly copied the stories and script word-for-word and panel-for-panel then what would the point be of seeing the movie?¬† We would already know what was going to happen!!!¬† All these movies are are different interpretations of the source material and thrown into an original story that can be appreciated, and understood, by those who may never have read the comics and those who have read the comics.¬† Finally, these movies are just for fun and shouldn't be taken seriously: after all, they are based on comic books!¬† So...if you're a fan boy know-it-all 1) It's cool you know what happens in the comics, but really, its not.¬† 2) No one else cares that you read the comics.¬† 3) When you belittle those of us who didn't read the comics it makes you look like a douche bag and a jerk.¬† Okay...I'm done now.¬† Have a good and get ready for X-Men: Days of Future Past!!!¬†

text: Everything from the overall casting (except Prof. X), single character focus, over extensive plots (which only work for single characters not teams), to the short movie lengths, never exploring full character potentials and just all-around bad writing and soap opera direction. The reason the Avengers worked was because their origin stories where spreaded out, that by the time you got to the team formation, there was nothing left to do but for them to kick butt. Now I know the X-men characters aren't as popular as the avengers to make individual movies, but they need to spread out the range somehow. Instead of it being the Wolverine show, with background characters and intricate plot.

text: Here's a single theory on 2 questions 1) How is Charles walking? 2) How does Beast return to human form. First, we now know Wolverine has nothing to do with Charles, seeing that Charles is walking when Wolverine first speaks to him. Beast continues to work on his serum/suppressor from First Class, making it better but not perfect, hence why we see both forms AND why his Beast form is more "human" and less cat like. And because this formula deals with restoring/rearranging physical tissue/whatever (as seen in First Class), Beast uses it on Charles to help him temporarily walk but because this formula isn't perfected he must still use his wheelchair at times, hence why we see him walking AND in his wheelchair in these trailers.

text: WTF! None of these movies stay true to X-Men lore. In the comics.. Nightcrawler is Mystique's son (which is in no way apparent in X2)... Rogue is Mystique's adopted daughter who Mystique convinces to kill Ms.Marvel (this is how she gains the ability to fly) BEFORE she is recruited by the X-men. In X-Men Origins they make Weapon XI (apparently a new creation of cinema) look like Deadpool (WTH!). Here Quicksilver is apparently very close in age to Magneto yet Magneto is Quicksilver's father. The sentinels here are ridiculously small as they were 30 feet tall in the comics. I could go on and on... I would love to see a proper rendition of Come the Apocalypse or some migration into the Age of Apocalypse storyline, but I hate to think what havoc they would wreak on one of the most powerful and revered villains the X-men have ever faced. Thanks hollywood, you continue to butcher The X-Men.

text: A few questions waiting to be answered: will Pietro be actually related to Erik? Why will Sentinels target humans? Why does Mystique and Magneto appear to not be part of the (a) brotherhood in this? Blink? Kitty?  I understand adapted stories are not direct from the pages but this seems to be a scenario where the pace of the script will be completely hampered by the runtime.   I'm as eager as the next X-Fan to see this but this will be dangerously close to being entirely convoluted. Nevermind pulling in two seperate movieverses in which the outcome will ultimately result in continuing with two seperate movieverses, from the rumored information floating out there.   Mainly im just eager/nervous to see how this is pulled off.

text: In my Overrall opinion on the change of kitty pryde to wolverine was completely sexist and embarrassing. Why I say embarrassing is beacsue there excuse so totally immature! Saying Oh "Wolverine is the most beloved character" is basically in my opinion another way of suger-coding saying that it should be a male role model with More experience. Why make a movie about the xmen original story if basically the whole entire movie is going to be changed? as a kitty pryde fan I was completely furious when I heard about this sudden change, and then it caused me to hate the wolverine character more then I had already did so. I agree with other peoples opinions saying that they over use wolverine as the main character in every movie. in My honest opinion I don't know why people like wolverine that much anyway! hes basically a male version of a badass cat. When I say they focus on him to much is like for example...- the story between phoenix "jean grey' and scott summers was one of the most important more cared about scenario in the xmen franchise and yet there hasn't been a movie about them, instead they put out a movie such as wolverine origens which really wasn't all that important and cared for. Back on the main topic, they could've made some adjustments that could still allow ellen page or kitty pryde to still be the leading character such as drag the time line earlier or something so she could actually be alive (if they could make a drastic move like replacing her completely the they could've done something like this) but instead on actually giving her a chance in the movie they completely replaced her. And anyone saying that main characters have to be well known are lying. If you look at first class Mystique, Banshee, pixie, havoc etc. weren't really known characters but they got to play a major role in the film portrayed as main characters. I just think this decision was utterly immature and stupid.

text: In my opinion, it's incredibly disappointing that they failed to cast Rebecca Romijn as Mystique. I don't know if there were contractual disputes with her, or if they felt that Jennifer Lawrence was now capable of taking on the role, but whatever the reason, it's wrong. Jennifer Lawrence is NOT Mystique. She is a better actress than Romijn - no doubt - but she cannot handle this role. She not only looks ridiculous in the make-up, but sounds ridiculous too. Mystique is a WOMAN. Not a girl. Rebecca Romijn should have been cast. Not only that, but Famke Janssen and James Marsden should have received larger roles as Jean Grey & Cyclops.  I understand they are trying to appeal to a younger demographic with these new films, but bring back the entire old cast already! Is it too much to ask to see the original cast band together again without the First Class cast along with them? I'm really disappointed that they are releasing a First Class sequel in 2017. I'm ready for X4 & X5. Come on already.

text: To those who have seen previous X-Men films, be warned that you may experience mild to severe cognitive dissonance.  If the Sentinels were introduced in the 70's, where were they in X-Men 1, 2, and 3?  Kitty Pride, who previously could walk through walls, now has the ability to transport someone's consciousness through time.  Despite previously being disintegrated by Jean Grey, Charles Xavier is now whole again. Though the scene after the credits of X-Men 3 revealed that his consciousness found its way to some guy in a coma, why would he still look exactly the same?  Judging from the age of some of the characters, the film takes place, at most, several years after the events of X-Men 3, but we somehow have technology of several decades after.  I would be fine if this movie completely disregarded the previous movies, but there are some things that it recognizes and some things that it disregards.  ¬†As entertaining as this film is, it's a continuity clusterfuck.

text: Good movie, go see it, I just don't understand how in the distant apocalyptic future, Magneto is still alive? I mean prof. He's got to be over 90 or 100 at the start of this movie, and I don't think he would be able to fight sentinels at that age.¬† What also wasn't explained was how Magneto got his powers back. He lost them at the end of the 3rd movie, and even though they hinted at how he still had some power remaining...did they just come back in full over time? Did this happen for other mutants as well? Mystique? Rouge?¬† How did Wolverine get his metal claws back? Are they adimantium?  Whatever, if you can ignore questions like these, and if Back to the Future wasn't too convoluted for you, you'll like this one.

text: I really wonder is the writers of the screenplay actually did much in depth research by actually reading the comic book series. Admittedly, the comic book series itself has some timeline "oddities", but the movie is over-the-top. (I'm referring to the original X-Men series, not the spinoffs.) The movie itself is a great flick. Fantastic special effects, great battle scenes, and really great acting. The plot is a simple one, but pulled off beautifully. As a devoted comic book junkie, I would recommend this film to anyone. It would be interesting to hear the opinions of the film from someone who isn't especially into the comic's scene. -side note- When I went to see the film, three quarters of the people in the theater were upper middle-age like myself. I thought that was a little surprising. I expected a younger audience.

text: ¬† Finally got some free time from work and was able to see this movie today and I must say that I thoroughly enjoyed it!  I have followed the X-men story since I was a kid (comics/animations/movies). Yes, the movie has been adjusted from the original story line in the comics, but the core message of the original plot line prevailed! Personally, I place more stock in that aspect rather than character/event changes made. X-men storylines have always appealed personally more to me than the Avengers storyline.  Seeing the emergence of Apocalypse and his four horsemen in the end credits got me wishing for the next installment immediately.Ôªø

text: Right now I'm making my own "fan fiction" which takes place a few months before the future of Days of Future Past (although the story starts in 2013). It features my own fan-made mutant (who I based off of myself because I like it that way and it's easier for me to write that way) named "Shapeshifter".  Shapeshifter has the mutant power to shapeshift into 11 different fictional creatures/monsters that he drew years prior to the discovery of his powers. Each creature is extremely dangerous (as described when he first discovers his powers).  Each creature has it's own amount of energy which means that after using one creature for a long time it will become very tired and vulnerable, if the creature is wounded the injury will carry on to his human form (as long as it doesn't involve limb loss or an injury that cannot carry over). When he shifts into a creature he gains it's abilities, resistances, and weaknesses. Shifter also has a "Rage mode" or "meltdown" which causes him to have a violent and aggressive fit in which he loses control and uses his powers to severely injure if not kill any Human, Mutant, or Android around him. This happens when Shifter is extremely angry (which can happen very easily), or if he is struck by high voltage natural electricity.  If Shifter is sent into shock, knocked unconscious, paralyzed, incapacitated, or frozen he will instantly morph back into human form.  His friends consist of  ‚Ä¢ LN2 (or Liquid Nitrogen, Cryokinesis abilities that are not unlike Iceman's however he cannot create an ice skin but instead can lower room temperatures low enough to freeze everything solid) ‚Ä¢Mantle (Pyrokinesis, can also set himself on fire with blue flames and can also manipulate/create Magma) ‚Ä¢ Leadman (equivalent to Colossus but instead has Lead) ‚Ä¢ and High Winds (can manipulate weather patterns involving wind)  The only rival I've written for Shapeshifter besides the Sentinels is the daughter of Meggan, Shelby (who has the same Shapeshifting abilities but can only shapeshift into creatures of legend such as Werewolves, Dragons, Loch Ness Monster, etc.) because after reading about Meggan's powers I thought she would be the perfect rival but she was too overpowered so I made a weaker version of her.  So anyways, the story will be all about Shapeshifter's discovery of his powers, going to Xavier's school, becoming an X-Men with his friends, and fighting off the Sentinels.  :-)  All of this was inspired by the movie because THE MOVIE WAS SO F-ING AWESOME! :-)

text: I watched "X-MEN: Days of Future Past" for the first time a month ago. The best X-MEN movie ever. 10/10!  Why? Many reasons. The story was great because it stayed on track for me and made sense the whole time. Great dialogue, A-list performances, and as always, Hugh Jackman and Jennifer Lawrence are in it, so what's not to like?  Criticism? A little. One problem I had was the great Jennifer Lawrence was given so little to do. She was almost like a standby character the whole time, a major problem since her character kinda carries the plot and conflict.   Also, a SERIOUS lack of action. OK, I know we got Quicksilver and a floating baseball stadium dropped around the White House, but other than that it felt slow and much calmer than all the other films.   Overall, an ace movie. I agree, it is the best X-MEN movie since X2. Just next time, maybe add five or ten more minutes of action in there, and then we'll talk.
